    <section id="datasect">
      <h3><strong>Data</strong></h3>
      Citizen science have much success when it comes to birding. Bird observation through citizen science data is amazingly rich and available to download either by requesting the data or an application programming interface or API access. 
        <ul>
        <li><a href="https://www.worldclim.org/data/bioclim.html">Bioclimatic data from WorldClim</a>.</li>
        <li><a href="https://ebird.org/science">eBird data</a>. <pkg>ebirdst</pkg> is a package that allows access and analyze eBird status and trends data</li>
        <li><a href="https://github.com/MotusWTS/motus">Motus Wildlife Tracking System</a> and <a href="https://github.com/MotusWTS/motusdata">Motus datasets</a> </li>
        <li><a href="https://github.com/birdstudiescanada/naturecounts">naturecounts:</a> Get observations from<a href="https://www.birdscanada.org/birdmon/default/main.jsp">NatureCounts</a></li>
        <li><a href="https://observation.org">Observation.org</a></li> (In development)
        <li><a href="https://www.pauljhurtado.com/US_Composite_Radar/">Radar images archive in the U.S.</a></li>
        <li><pkg>rgbif</pkg>: Global Biodiversity Information Facility <a href="https://www.gbif.org">(gbif)</a> data access with an API</li>
        <li><pkg>rinat</pkg>: <a href="https://www.inaturalist.org/pages/how+can+i+use+it">iNaturalist</a> data access through an API</li>
        </ul>
    </section>


